<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-826-988  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 826 988.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Oct 30 1989 v6 n43 p19(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Academics at Educom '89 lament cost of technology; future ofeducation depends on affordable nets.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>DiDio, Laura.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A major theme at the Educom '89 conference was the excessive costof networking technology.andP;  Only a small percentage of universitiesand colleges are able to afford sophisticated computer andcommunication systems.andP;  According to one speaker, a properlyeducated society can only be realized if networking technology isavailable to all institutions.andP;  Of the 250 institutions linked tothe National Science Foundation's BitNet electronic mail network,only 24 are small colleges.andP;  Membership in a statewide or regionalnetwork costs between $10,000 and $50,000.andP;  The $500,000 price tagfor membership in BitNet excludes about 90 percent of theeducational institutions in the US.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     EducomEducationCost of CommunicationsMISColleges and UniversitiesConferencesNetworks.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>